data.name: toolStripComboBox_MainTool_AutoAction_Trigger.ToolTipText
data.value:
Configure Automatic Action Trigger.
Either refer to one of the commands, or fill in any sequence of bytes, e.g. "<ETB><NUL>" or "\h(17 00)", or any other parseable text, e.g. ";". The trigger will be based on the resulting byte sequence of the command.
Optionally, [Use Text] to switch to a trigger based on the resulting text. With this option, optionally [Enable Regular Expression]. Some useful expression patterns (use without surrounding quotes):
Integral numbers: "([-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in normal format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+))" Floating point numbers in scientific format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)[Ee][-+]?\d+)" Floating point numbers in any format: "([-+]?(?:\d+(?:\.\d*)?|\.\d+)(?:[Ee][-+]?\d+)?)" Time with colons (e.g. 12:00:00): "((?:[01]\d|2[0-3]):(?:[0-5]\d):(?:[0-5]\d))" Date with hyphens (e.g. 2000-01-01): "((?:19|20)\d\d-(?:0[1-9]|1[012])-(?:0[1-9]|[12]\d|3[01]))" A single capital letter: "\b([A-Z]{1})\b" A string of 2..4 letters: "\b([A-Za-z]{2,4})\b"
Google for ".NET Regular Expression Quick Reference" for details on syntax. Google for "C# Regex Tester" for online tools to help creating regular expressions. It is recommended to test regular expression patterns before applying them.
Note that... ...[Any Line] is not available if action is [Highlight] or [Suppress], as that would result in all received lines being highlighted or suppressed. ...same as other actions, [Filter] and [Suppress] are only applied to received data. ...[Plot ... Count/Rate] are applied to any trigger and to received as well as sent data.

data.name: toolStripComboBox_MainTool_AutoAction_Action.ToolTipText
data.value:
Enable / Disable Automatic Action
[Line/Scatter/Histogram] require a trigger that is based on a regular expression containing at least one capture (i.e. a pattern in parentheses, e.g. "(\d+)") which is used to retrieve the values to plot.
All captures will be treated as Y values, unless for actions stating "(X = ...)" where the first capture will be treated as the X value.
Date/Time values are converted to "OLE Automation Date" values. Google that term for details.
Captures that can neither be converted to an integral nor floating point number, nor a date/time value, are treated as strings. Strings are converted to a value by summing the code of each character. This allows plotting elements defined by characters (e.g. A, B, C) or even whole strings.
Note that... ...trigger is highlighted for every action except [Filter], [Suppress] and [Line/Scatter/Histogram]. ...[Highlight] and [Suppress] is not available if trigger is [Any Line], as that would result in all received lines being highlighted or suppressed. ...same as other actions, [Filter] and [Suppress] are only applied to received data. ...[Plot ... Count/Rate] are applied to any trigger and to received as well as sent data.

data.name: toolStripButton_MainTool_AutoResponse_Response_EnableReplace.ToolTipText
data.value:
Enable Replace [Alt+R] (while editing)
Requires a trigger that is based on a regular expression containing at least one capture (i.e. a pattern in parentheses, e.g. "(\d+)") because replacement is done based on regular expression captures.
Example usage: > Trigger = (\d+)ABC > Response = $1XYZ Receiving e.g. 99ABC will trigger the response, 99 being captured by (\d+). The $1 replacement tag will be filled with 99, resulting in sending 99XYZ.
Replacement tags are $1, $2,... (regular expression syntax).
